deck: British company which produces audio dramas, and which, in 2012, expanded into publishing a comic based on one of those dramas.
description:
In 2007 Cosmic Hobo Productions launched a series of audio dramas, The Scarifyers, following the adventures of Whitechapel police officer Detective Inspector Lionheart (played by Nicholas Courtney, best known as the Brigadier in Doctor Who) and ghost-story novelist Professor Edward Dunning (played by Terry Molloy, who played Davros in Doctor Who) in the late 1930s as they work for Britain's supernatural investigation division, MI-13 (no relation to Captain Britain's MI13). The stories, initially available on CD, were swiftly picked up for broacast by BBC 7. After Courtney's demise in 2011, his character was written out the series, with David Warner joining as Harry "Thumper" Crow, Lionheart's former sergeant.

In 2012, Cosmic Hobo began publishing a comic adaptation of The Scarifyers, starting with their first adventure, The Nazad Conspiracy.
name: Cosmic Hobo

description: Craig Partin (Founder/Writer), Stuart Berryhill (Artist/Inker), and Jonathan Swinney (Letterer/Project Manager) met in 2008 via a "dead universe" forum board called Valiantfans.com. At the request of Valiant Entertainment founder and COO, DineshShamdasani, the trio created the web comic Playing God. After being offered in 18 separate, 5 page web chapters, the book was bound in TPB form and released in 2009. Joined by penciller Yvel Guichet (DC, Dark Horse, Valiant) and cover artist Dan Brereton (The Nocturnals) the trio began work on the long gestating Man of God. A supernatural horror mystery set over the backdrop of a brewing mob war. Man of God is a dark, often violent, tale of redemption and the quest for the truth.
name: Pinwheel Press

deck: Star Comics was an imprint of Marvel Comics that started in 1984 focusing on comics mainly for kids or younger teens.
description:
Brief History

Star Comics began in 1984 and continued to publish comic books until the early 1988's when the series that where still published by Star Comics where inserted in the regular Marvel Comics line. Titles published by the imprint were aimed at child readers and were often adaptations of children's television series, animated series or toys. Several of the original titles consciously emulated the house writing and visual style of then recently defunct Harvey Comics titles such as Richie Rich.
 
The publisher had many original characters among their published comics, such as 
- Planet Terry
- Royal Roy
- Top Dog
- Wally the Wizard
Even Spider-Ham was published by the Star Comics imprint for the main part of the run.
name: Star Comics
